      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_414gc' title='Col. 414GC &mdash; HL Deb 29 March 2004 vol 659 c414GC' name='column_414gc' href='#column_414gc' rel='bookmark'>414GC</a>
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0659P0-06512'>
        <a name='S5LV0659P0_20040329_GCR_244'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-sainsbury' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0659P0_20040329_GCR_244' title='Link to this speech by Mr David Sainsbury' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-david-sainsbury" title="Mr David Sainsbury">Lord Sainsbury of Turville</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I am absolutely delighted. I thought I would be able to make one noble Lord happy today: I can obviously make two Peers happy. We are very grateful to the noble Lord for the amendment.</p><p>
            In practice, we think that the remedy, which the regulator is seeking, when bringing proceedings will often be evident from the other information that the Bill requires to be included in the notice given to the CIC. However, where it is not, it will certainly be helpful to the CIC concerned if the remedy sought is made clear. We therefore agree to consider the amendment.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0659P0-06513'>
        <a name='S5LV0659P0_20040329_GCR_245'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-andrew-phillips' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0659P0_20040329_GCR_245' title='Link to this speech by Mr Andrew Phillips' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
